        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request 2.19 hrs of on-source band 9 imaging at 0.41" resolution of
the clumpy HUDF disk CDFS-2954.  Including calibration and overheads,
this amounts to a total of 5.74 hrs.

** Resolution and Galaxy Structure **

The requested resolution is demanded by the internal structure of our
target, in order to adequately identify and disentangle the central
region, outer disk and off-center clumps, for which we aim to
constrain the bolometric star formation rate and obscuration
individually.  In H-band light, our target has a semi-major axis
length of 5.7 kpc and axial ratio of 0.6.  Given the negative color
gradient (i.e., red center), the size increases when measured at
shorter wavelengths, with blue off-center clumps spread over a total
extent of 2" (17 kpc) along the major axis.

** Why band 9? **

Band 9 observations are critical for our scientific objectives, even
though restricted in schedulability due to the required optimal
weather conditions.  At z=2.128, band 9 probes the dust continuum at a
rest-wavelength of 140 micron, sufficiently close to the peak of the
infrared emission to reliably estimate the spatial distribution of the
total infrared luminosity, whose galaxy-integrated value is known to
be 10^12 Lsun from Herschel photometry.  Here, we assume the dust
temperature does not vary spatially across the galaxy.  If it does, at
the level of 5 K, this induces an uncertainty of 25-30% in the
translation to L_IR(8-1000micron).  Observations at longer wavelengths
would be significantly more sensitive to dust temperature variations,
with errors increasing to 50-60% in band 6 and higher at longer
wavelengths.

** Requested depth **

Adopting the formal best-fit dust temperature of 38 K, the total
infrared luminosity of 10^12 Lsun corresponds to a galaxy-integrated
band 9 flux density of 2.9 mJy.  Assuming the spatial distribution of
the infrared luminosity is clumpy, peaking at the locations of the 4
clumps seen in UV emission, we expect peak flux densities per 0.41"
beam of around 0.75 mJy.  ALMA in cycle 2 has sufficient sensitivity
to map this at the 5sigma level (i.e., with a sensitivity per pointing
of 0.15 mJy) in 2.19 hours on source (5.74 hours total).  The
alternative scenario, in which the blue off-center clumps are merely
holes in the dust and the majority of infrared emission originates
from the central 1-2 beam areas of the galaxy, would yield an even
higher level of significance (5-10 sigma) in the same observing time.
In a scenario where the distribution is smoother, with 60% of the
infrared luminosity in a diffuse component, the corresponding flux
measurements per beam are marginally significant (2-3 sigma), in which
case we will extract statistically more robust results by stacking the
galaxy center, outer disk and clump regions separately in a similar
fashion as successfully applied by Wuyts et al. (2012, 2013).

We note that the dust temperature of 38 K is poorly constrained by the
depth of the Herschel/SPIRE data, and colder dust temperatures are
formally allowed by the fit.  Magnelli et al. (2013) finds a
characteristic dust temperature of 32 K for galaxies of similar
redshift, mass and star formation rate as CDFS-2954.  Applying this
colder dust temperature, anticipated band 9 flux densities increase by
a factor 1.6.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
