        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request 3.42 hrs of on-source band 3 observations at 0.41"
resolution to measure the spatial distribution of the CO(3-2)
rotational transition line in the clumpy HUDF disk CDFS-2954.
Including calibration and overheads, this amounts to a total of 6.42
hrs.

** Resolution and Galaxy Structure **

The requested resolution is demanded by the internal structure of our
target, in order to adequately identify and disentangle the central
region, outer disk and off-center clumps, for which we aim to
constrain the bolometric star formation rate and obscuration
individually.  In H-band light, our target has a semi-major axis
length of 5.7 kpc and axial ratio of 0.6.  Given the negative color
gradient (i.e., red center), the size increases when measured at
shorter wavelengths, with blue off-center clumps spread over a total
extent of 2" (17 kpc) along the major axis.

** Requested depth **

We computed the anticipated CO(3-2) line flux from the bolometric (UV
+ Herschel) star formation rate of 110 Msun/yr of CDFS-2954, assuming
a depletion time of 0.7 Gyr.  This is the typical depletion time for
normal z ~ 2 star-forming galaxies, as quantified on the largest CO
data set of such galaxies obtained by the PHIBSS survey with the IRAM
Platea de Bure Interferometer (Tacconi et al. 2013).  The [NII]/Halpha
line ratio of 0.35 for CDFS-2954 implies near-solar metallicities,
justifying the use of a standard conversion factor in translating the
inferred molecular gas mass to a CO flux density.  We adopt a default
CO(3-2)/CO(1-0) ratio of 0.5 and obtain an integrated CO(3-2) line
flux of 0.33 Jy km/s.  Given the 212 km/s line width of our SINFONI
Halpha emission line observations, this translates to 1.54 mJy.
Following a similar line of reasoning as for the band 9 continuum
observations, we considered three scenarios for the molecular gas
distribution: one in which it clumped peaking at the locations where
also the UV clumps are seen, a second in which the CO emission is
centrally peaked corresponding to the location of the highest dust
column, and finally a more diffuse morphology.  In the former two
scenarios, anticipated peak flux densities are in the range 0.4 - 0.7
mJy/beam, which can be measured at the &gt;5 sigma significance level in
3.42 hours on source, yielding a sensitivity of 0.08 mJy/beam
integrated over the full 212 km/s line width.  If instead the CO flux
distribution is largely diffuse, the significance level per beam will
drop to around 2 sigma, but powerful constraints on depletion times of
clumps compared to the rest of the galaxy can still be obtained
through a stacking methodology of regions pre-selected on the
multi-wavelength HST imagery to belong to the galaxy center, clump or
interclump regime (see Wuyts et al. 2012, 2013 for successful
applications of this strategy).
</prj:justificationText>
