    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to obtain deep, high-resolution continuum imaging in band 9
of a star-forming clumpy disk at z=2.128.  Located in the Hubble Ultra
Deep Field, this map of the far-infrared emission together with the
deepest rest-UV imaging ever taken, will yield the first bolometric
star formation rate distribution on sub-galactic scales of a normal
galaxy during the peak of cosmic star formation.  It will allow us to
calibrate extinction corrections to the resolved Halpha and UV
emission observed by VLT/SINFONI and the Hubble Space Telescope, and
to address the nature of clumps in marginally stable disks.  We
further propose to map the CO(3-2) rotational transition line on the
same 0.41" scale to complete the resolved baryonic mass budget,
contrast it to the dynamical mass profile from Halpha kinematics, shed
light on depletion time variations between the galaxy center,
off-center clumps, and diffuse outer disk, and investigate the
relation between the optical depth and the molecular gas column of
sub-galactic components.  Our study will provide unique insights into
the structural build-up and regulation of star formation within early
disks.</prp:abstract>
